moves through life faster.

30:08.577 --> 30:10.042
In one day, one can open,

30:10.044 --> 30:14.516
it can change color,
wilt, and then die.

30:16.518 --> 30:17.951
Look...
Here, pass it, pass it.

30:17.953 --> 30:19.886
Sometimes
the things that you say...

30:19.888 --> 30:21.721
Left or right?

30:21.723 --> 30:23.388
Uh... Uh, why?

30:23.390 --> 30:25.290
It's very, very important.

30:25.292 --> 30:27.328
- (CAR HORN HONKING)
- You choose.

30:29.531 --> 30:32.364
Basically,
if you choose your left,

30:32.366 --> 30:35.033
it means you are technically
off the market,

30:35.035 --> 30:36.769
you're in a relationship.

30:36.771 --> 30:38.439
- Ooh.
- Yeah, so it's...

30:39.039 --> 30:40.640
Well...

30:40.642 --> 30:43.208
Wow, wise choice. Wise choice.

30:43.210 --> 30:45.845
(SOFT OPERATIC MUSIC PLAYING)

30:45.847 --> 30:47.714
- TAMI: Seven years?
- Mmm-hmm.

30:47.716 --> 30:49.749
Wow.

30:49.751 --> 30:51.049
So that would mean
that when you were

30:51.051 --> 30:52.819
beginning to work
on the <i>Mayaluga,</i>

30:52.821 --> 30:55.222
I was celebrating my sweet 16?

30:55.790 --> 30:57.091
- (LAUGHS)
- Yep.

30:57.726 --> 30:58.958
Jeez.

30:58.960 --> 31:01.895
And was it sweet, your 16th?

31:01.897 --> 31:05.264
No. No, my mom
took me to my first bar.

31:05.266 --> 31:07.934
I had like 10 shots
of Midori...

31:07.936 --> 31:09.167
Oh, my Lord.

31:09.169 --> 31:11.938
Yeah. Worst hangover
of my life, hands down.

31:11.940 --> 31:14.841
So your mum's a wild one, eh?

31:14.843 --> 31:16.341
One of those
young-at-heart types?

31:16.343 --> 31:19.946
Oh, she's just young, period.
She was 31.

31:19.948 --> 31:21.346
Oh, when she had you?

31:21.348 --> 31:23.583
No. No, that night.

31:23.585 --> 31:25.352
She was 15 when she had me.

31:26.053 --> 31:26.986
Wow.

31:26.988 --> 31:29.956
Got knocked up
when she was just a kid.

31:29.958 --> 31:31.423
Had me out of defiance.

31:31.425 --> 31:34.061
My dad's parents
actually raised me.

31:35.362 --> 31:36.763
What was that like?

31:36.765 --> 31:39.066
It was what I knew.
I don't know.

31:40.100 --> 31:44.102
I made attempts, of course,
to run away.

31:44.104 --> 31:45.838
But Mom worked for TWA,

31:45.840 --> 31:47.774
and I think her
not being around as much

31:47.776 --> 31:49.541
kind of forced me
to stick around.

31:49.543 --> 31:50.977
Like I owed it to her

31:50.979 --> 31:53.580
to finish high school
or something.

31:53.582 --> 31:55.917
- That makes sense.
- I guess.

31:57.184 --> 32:00.920
But, man,
the day I graduated, I split.

32:00.922 --> 32:02.321
My girlfriend and I
had been saving up,

32:02.323 --> 32:04.991
and we bought the sickest bus,

32:04.993 --> 32:07.392
drove it across the border
to Todos Santos

32:07.394 --> 32:10.697
and just lived on the beach
for a few months.

32:10.699 --> 32:12.031
We started a salsa company

32:12.033 --> 32:14.199
and surfed every day.
It was...

32:14.201 --> 32:17.204
(EXHALES) It was amazing.

32:17.939 --> 32:19.371
Plan was to stay
for six months,

32:19.373 --> 32:23.645
but it's been five years
and here I am...

32:25.512 --> 32:26.547
Here you are.

32:27.816 --> 32:29.316
(LAUGHS)

32:30.051 --> 32:31.886
You ready to shake, old salt?

32:32.419 --> 32:33.518
(LAUGHS) Sorry...

32:33.520 --> 32:36.055
- Can I say no? No. No, no.
- Yes. Yes.

32:36.057 --> 32:37.524
(BOTH LAUGH)

32:39.928 --> 32:42.527
(POLYNESIAN MUSIC PLAYING)

32:42.529 --> 32:45.263
- Oh, you have been warned.
- (BOTH LAUGH)

32:45.265 --> 32:48.067
I'm sorry this...
This is the best I've got.

32:48.069 --> 32:51.536
No, you've got more in there,
I know it. (LAUGHS)

32:51.538 --> 32:55.207
Oh, no. No,
you're a much better dancer.

32:55.209 --> 32:56.678
TAMI: It's the dress.

32:57.344 --> 32:58.276
It is the dress.

32:58.278 --> 32:59.812
That's why you bought it
for me.

32:59.814 --> 33:01.546
Ah, got me.

33:01.548 --> 33:02.483
(MUSIC ENDS)

33:04.819 --> 33:07.287
(SOFT POLYNESIAN MUSIC
PLAYING)

33:20.735 --> 33:21.934
Hey, Tami...

33:21.936 --> 33:23.170
Yeah?

33:25.974 --> 33:28.242
Will you sail around the world
with me?

33:29.144 --> 33:30.679
(TAMI CHUCKLES SOFTLY)

33:39.286 --> 33:41.990
(RICHARD WINCING, GROANING)

33:43.190 --> 33:44.857
TAMI: Exhale for me.

33:44.859 --> 33:46.961
(RICHARD BREATHING SHARPLY)

33:49.363 --> 33:50.631
(GROANS)

33:51.066 --> 33:53.465
(TAMI SHUSHES)

33:53.467 --> 33:56.836
- Hey, it's okay. It's done.
- (GROANS)

33:56.838 --> 33:58.139
Just breathe.

34:01.608 --> 34:02.775
(GROANING LOUDLY)

34:02.777 --> 34:04.209
What? What, what, what, what?

34:04.211 --> 34:05.747
My ribs. My ribs. My ribs.

34:06.848 --> 34:09.150
Oh, my God. Oh, my God.

34:14.487 --> 34:15.987
(RICHARD PANTING)

34:15.989 --> 34:17.522
TAMI: Put your arm around me.

34:17.524 --> 34:21.328
- Ready? One, two, three, lift.
- (RICHARD GROANS)

34:22.262 --> 34:23.963
- Okay, okay...
- (RICHARD COUGHS)

34:23.965 --> 34:25.766
(TAMI SHUSHING)

34:34.241 --> 34:37.509
- (COUGHS, GROANS)
- Shh.

34:37.511 --> 34:38.445
(RICHARD CHUCKLES)

34:41.581 --> 34:44.416
What about Fatu Hiva?
We could sail there first.

34:44.418 --> 34:46.351
It could work.
It could work, yeah.

34:46.353 --> 34:48.620
As long as we don't
go through Hana Vave.

34:48.621 --> 34:51.090
Everyone goes through it,
it's become a bit of a dump.

34:51.092 --> 34:52.657
Oh, what's the draw then?

34:52.659 --> 34:54.062
Better anchorage.

34:54.795 --> 34:56.360
Lazy suckers.

34:56.362 --> 34:58.197
Omoa Bay. Now that...

34:58.199 --> 35:00.800
That is, I mean,
that is <i>parfait.</i>

35:00.802 --> 35:02.135
Yeah? What, the beaches?

35:02.137 --> 35:05.106
Yeah.
Just like beyond amazing.

35:06.107 --> 35:09.041
(BOTH SPEAK FRENCH)

35:09.043 --> 35:10.877
(IN ENGLISH) What about Japan?

35:10.879 --> 35:12.945
I've always wanted
to check it out.

35:12.947 --> 35:14.213
- Are you kidding me?
- Mmm-mmm.

35:14.215 --> 35:16.249
It's like
my number one place, like...

35:16.251 --> 35:17.716
- Really?
- Yeah.

35:17.718 --> 35:18.719
We gotta go.

35:19.821 --> 35:20.287
How long do you think
it would take to sail there?

35:21.122 --> 35:23.122
- Forever. But does it matter?
- No.

35:23.124 --> 35:25.958
No. God, I just want to go
everywhere with you.

35:25.960 --> 35:27.126
Then everywhere we will go.

35:27.128 --> 35:29.694
WOMAN: Richard! Richard!

35:29.696 --> 35:30.764
MAN: Richard!

35:31.800 --> 35:35.433
- (MAN LAUGHS)
- What? Tally-ho!

35:35.435 --> 35:36.768
MAN: Where the hell
have you been hiding?

35:36.770 --> 35:38.770
How are you, mate? (LAUGHS)

35:38.772 --> 35:40.173
Oh, just everywhere.

35:40.175 --> 35:41.373
WOMAN: Good to see you,
Richard.

35:41.375 --> 35:43.608
I nearly rang the bloody
coast guard. (LAUGHS)

35:43.610 --> 35:47.146
Sorry. Sorry, this is...
This is Tami. Tami.

35:47.148 --> 35:48.214
- Hi.
- Christine.

35:48.216 --> 35:49.714
- Christine. Peter.
- Nice to meet you.

35:49.716 --> 35:50.617
- Hi, my pleasure.
- Same.

35:51.618 --> 35:52.985
Tami. Yeah, well...
How have you guys been?

35:52.987 --> 35:54.352
- Oh, really good.
- Great.

35:54.354 --> 35:56.590
We were just off for a coffee,
do you want to join us?

35:57.791 --> 36:00.059
PETER: I'm glad we bumped
into you, Richard, because...

36:00.061 --> 36:01.127
Well, there's something
we'd like

36:01.129 --> 36:02.195
to talk to you about,
actually.

36:02.197 --> 36:03.428
CHRISTINE:
The thing is, Richard,

36:03.430 --> 36:04.864
we've got to go back to London
rather suddenly,

36:04.866 --> 36:07.099
and we wanted to ask
if you'd be interested in...

36:07.101 --> 36:08.600
Yeah, we've been trying
to find someone,

36:08.602 --> 36:11.469
and I don't know
if you'd be keen, but...

36:11.471 --> 36:13.039
How'd you like
to sail the <i>Hazana</i>

36:13.041 --> 36:14.641
back to California for us?

36:17.879 --> 36:19.278
We can pay $10,000

36:19.280 --> 36:21.348
plus a first-class ticket
return.

36:22.851 --> 36:24.349
Seriously?

36:24.351 --> 36:27.352
You're...
You're joking, right?

36:27.354 --> 36:29.021
- No, mate.
- No.

36:29.023 --> 36:30.223
PETER: What do you say?

36:30.225 --> 36:32.490
(LAUGHS) Uh...

36:32.492 --> 36:34.659
(LAUGHS) Where...
Where in California?

36:34.661 --> 36:36.898
- PETER: San Diego.
- (TAMI CHUCKLES)

36:38.599 --> 36:40.400
Wow. (CHUCKLES)

36:40.902 --> 36:43.102
Uh... I don't mean

36:43.104 --> 36:45.704
to look a gift horse
in the mouth here,

36:45.706 --> 36:51.212
but is there any possibility
of making it two tickets back?

36:53.081 --> 36:55.647
Done and done.

36:55.649 --> 36:59.653
Done and done. Brilliant!
Wow. That is... (LAUGHS)

37:00.721 --> 37:01.954
When do you leave?

37:01.956 --> 37:04.323
Well, we're hoping to get out
no later than next week.

37:04.325 --> 37:06.092
And the things is,
we don't want to press you,

37:06.094 --> 37:07.226
but it would be great
if you could

37:07.228 --> 37:09.095
let us know
when you could set sail.

37:09.097 --> 37:11.596
Mmm-hmm. Yeah, we can do that.

37:11.598 --> 37:13.167
- CHRISTINE: Great.
- We can, um,

37:14.302 --> 37:16.603
- mull it over. (LAUGHS)
- (CHRISTINE LAUGHS)

37:31.418 --> 37:33.551
Are you sure
you want to put me in charge

37:33.553 --> 37:34.488
of these numbers?

37:35.856 --> 37:37.691
I'm shit at math.

37:39.493 --> 37:43.097
You can do anything
you put your mind to.

37:45.333 --> 37:47.434
Mom used to tell me
the same thing.

37:48.568 --> 37:52.240
And then she would say that
my mind was too strong.

37:54.242 --> 37:57.111
Probably should have just been
more like her, huh?

37:59.147 --> 38:02.716
Have kids by now.
Live in the suburbs somewhere.

38:03.684 --> 38:05.517
Well, I'd still be
in the Naval Academy

38:05.519 --> 38:07.221
if I'd listened to me dad.

38:10.992 --> 38:13.527
But I decided to live
my own life.

38:22.736 --> 38:23.804
(SIGHS)

38:25.173 --> 38:26.640
(METAL CREAKING)

38:28.542 --> 38:29.743
We're...

38:30.744 --> 38:32.380
We're so far north!

38:34.215 --> 38:36.417
Well, we are drifting.

38:36.883 --> 38:37.884
How far?

38:38.987 --> 38:41.222
Way further than I thought.

38:42.190 --> 38:43.623
What's the latitude?

38:45.994 --> 38:48.162
Eighteen degrees north.

38:55.036 --> 38:58.638
That's like a fifteen hundred
square mile search area...

39:00.341 --> 39:03.311
- (TAMI SIGHS)
- (GROANS)

39:05.480 --> 39:07.681
We're gonna die out here.

39:16.090 --> 39:19.025
We're not on any flight paths,

39:19.027 --> 39:21.329
there's no shipping lanes...

39:23.597 --> 39:24.598
Tami...

39:25.466 --> 39:27.768
No one knows we're here.

39:29.303 --> 39:30.637
We'll be fine.

39:32.073 --> 39:33.508
(SNIFFLES)

39:35.609 --> 39:36.777
(EXHALES)

39:52.427 --> 39:53.560
Hey.

39:54.628 --> 39:55.829
Hey.

40:11.212 --> 40:12.413
You okay?

40:13.914 --> 40:14.879
I don't want to feel like

40:14.881 --> 40:16.783
I'm following you
on your adventures.

40:20.321 --> 40:24.858
I get that it's
a really cool opportunity,

40:27.694 --> 40:30.831
but I'm not really looking
to go home yet.

40:32.200 --> 40:34.968
It's not the direction
I wanna go in,

40:35.836 --> 40:39.340
and if that's what
you want, then...

40:43.610 --> 40:44.611
I'm sorry.

40:51.152 --> 40:52.284
I'm not going.

40:52.286 --> 40:54.455
I'm not asking you to do that.

40:54.888 --> 40:55.889
I know.

40:58.493 --> 41:00.994
I sailed half the world
to find you.

41:03.997 --> 41:05.632
I'm not just letting that go.

41:15.443 --> 41:16.643
(CHUCKLING) What?

41:17.978 --> 41:19.380
Ugh. (CHUCKLES)

41:19.813 --> 41:21.081
(LAUGHS)

41:24.117 --> 41:26.420
Well, can I see
this big bad boat?

41:40.401 --> 41:42.102
- The boat's fifty-five feet...
- (BEEPS)

41:44.037 --> 41:47.105
(GRUNTING) Fourteen seconds...

41:47.107 --> 41:50.444
Means we're going about
two... two-and-a-half knots.

41:53.614 --> 41:58.082
We could hit San Diego
in twenty-five days.

41:58.084 --> 42:01.686
But then with these headwinds,
it could take months...

42:01.688 --> 42:04.458
Well, what if we don't sail
to San Diego?

42:05.825 --> 42:07.093
What do you mean?

42:08.061 --> 42:09.397
TAMI: I mean,

42:10.364 --> 42:13.365
what if we hang left
and we go to Hawaii?

42:13.367 --> 42:15.702
Like navigators did
back in the day.

42:17.037 --> 42:20.206
Yeah, but most of those
sailors didn't make it, Tam.

42:20.208 --> 42:21.340
If you miss Hawaii...

42:21.342 --> 42:23.043
I know,
there's nothing till Japan.

42:24.212 --> 42:27.615
It's like a two thousand mile
shot at a moving target.

42:30.384 --> 42:31.851
If we miss Hawaii, we die.

42:32.819 --> 42:35.887
We'd be adding
five hundred miles.

42:35.889 --> 42:38.925
Yeah, but the current and
the wind would be behind us.

42:40.860 --> 42:42.496
(TAMI SIGHS)

42:43.297 --> 42:44.862
RICHARD: Okay.

42:44.864 --> 42:46.833
Take a left
on the nineteenth...

42:51.171 --> 42:52.172
TAMI: Yeah.

42:53.441 --> 42:55.443
(CREAKING)

43:26.773 --> 43:28.641
CHRISTINE: The moment we hit
the dock, I cried out,

43:28.643 --> 43:31.510
"God, I'm glad to be back
in Rangiroa!"

43:31.512 --> 43:32.678
PETER:
There's a fellow nearby,

43:32.680 --> 43:34.747
he looks to his wife
and he says to us,

43:34.749 --> 43:36.814
"You're not in Rangiroa...

43:36.816 --> 43:38.883
- "You're in Apataki."
- No.

43:38.885 --> 43:40.753
How?
That's like 100 miles away!

43:40.755 --> 43:42.721
- Yeah, no shit.
- (ALL CHUCKLE)

43:42.723 --> 43:44.523
The longest sail of my life,
Richard.

43:44.525 --> 43:46.694
- Sorry about that, darling.
- (LAUGHTER)

43:47.295 --> 43:48.627
Well, cheers, everyone.

43:48.629 --> 43:50.928
ALL: Cheers.

43:50.930 --> 43:52.698
What's the, uh... What's
the rush back to London,

43:52.700 --> 43:54.899
- if you don't mind me asking?
- Ah.

43:54.901 --> 43:58.771
Well, it's Christine's father,
he's not well.

43:58.773 --> 44:00.675
TAMI: Oh.
RICHARD: I'm sorry.

44:01.542 --> 44:03.241
Will he be okay?

44:03.243 --> 44:04.743
He's ninety-four.

44:04.745 --> 44:06.612
It's a good innings.

44:06.614 --> 44:08.114
You'd be a life-saver,
Richard.

44:14.722 --> 44:16.388
Wow.

44:16.390 --> 44:18.757
This is beautiful. (CHUCKLES)

44:18.759 --> 44:20.224
Oh, Richard.
We're out of ginger beer...

44:20.226 --> 44:23.261
We're just gonna go and grab
some from the clubhouse. Okay?

44:23.263 --> 44:25.930
Make yourselves at home.
We'll be back in a while.

44:25.932 --> 44:26.866
Thanks.

44:29.503 --> 44:32.136
(TAMI SNICKERING)

44:32.138 --> 44:36.007
So, what do you think of
the big bad boat then?

44:36.009 --> 44:39.045
I think four thousand miles
is insane...

44:40.847 --> 44:42.748
Yeah, but

44:42.750 --> 44:45.484
in a month
we'd make enough to fund

44:45.486 --> 44:47.586
an entire year
traveling together.

44:47.588 --> 44:49.854
- Oh, a year?
- Ah.

44:49.856 --> 44:52.056
Who said anything
about a year?

44:52.058 --> 44:55.663
(EXHALES) Why are you
trying to get rid of me?

44:56.630 --> 44:58.932
Why are you
trying to have sex with me?

44:59.467 --> 45:01.669
Why not? Here?

45:03.637 --> 45:05.471
I mean, it's our boat now,
so why not?

45:05.473 --> 45:06.940
(EXCLAIMS)

45:07.941 --> 45:09.075
So you're in?

45:10.544 --> 45:12.713
Just for those first-class
plane tickets.

45:18.318 --> 45:20.151
Whoa.

45:20.153 --> 45:23.689
- Later, you dirty old man.
- Come on.

45:23.691 --> 45:25.793
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

45:32.666 --> 45:36.535
TAMI: <i>Dear Mum,
sorry it's been a while.</i>

45:36.537 --> 45:40.574
<i>I wanted to let you know that
I am going to be coming home.</i>

45:42.476 --> 45:44.942
<i>I got this job sailing
this gorgeous yacht</i>

45:44.944 --> 45:47.147
<i>from down here
back to San Diego.</i>

45:48.649 --> 45:50.917
(GRUNTING)

45:51.985 --> 45:53.452
(GROANS)

45:53.454 --> 45:55.554
<i>It's about
a thirty-day crossing,</i>

45:55.556 --> 45:58.893
<i>so hopefully we'll get there
right before Halloween.</i>

45:59.827 --> 46:01.325
- Come on, come on, come on.
- (WHIRRING)

46:01.327 --> 46:04.832
(GASPS) It looks like we have
a quarter tank of water!

46:09.936 --> 46:11.570
<i>I really hope you're in town</i>

46:11.572 --> 46:13.806
<i>because I'm going
to be bringing</i>

46:13.808 --> 46:16.677
<i>my new boyfriend.</i> (CHUCKLES)

46:18.278 --> 46:19.912
<i>His name is Richard.</i>

46:19.914 --> 46:23.682
<i>He's a little bit older.
Uh, he's from England.</i>

46:23.684 --> 46:26.951
<i>We've only been together
a few months now,</i>

46:26.953 --> 46:30.589
<i>but, I don't know, I really
feel like he's the one.</i>

46:30.591 --> 46:32.058
DEB: Bon voyage, lovers.

46:32.992 --> 46:34.392
TAMI: <i>I guess we'll find out</i>

46:34.394 --> 46:37.995
<i>after crossing the Pacific
together.</i> (CHUCKLES)

46:37.997 --> 46:39.065
<i>Anyway,</i>

46:40.233 --> 46:42.468
<i>I can't wait to see you
and Gram and Grandpa.</i>

46:42.470 --> 46:44.969
<i>Dad, if he's around.</i>

46:44.971 --> 46:47.106
<i>I'll see you soon.
I love you so much.</i>

46:48.876 --> 46:50.776
(GROANS) That's it.

46:50.778 --> 46:52.813
We've eaten
all the fresh stuff.

46:55.516 --> 46:57.383
Ouch. (EXHALES)

46:57.785 --> 46:59.651
Is this it?

46:59.653 --> 47:02.255
Yeah. It's everything
I could salvage.

47:03.657 --> 47:07.193
- Here. You need to drink this.
- (EXHALES)

47:09.964 --> 47:10.965
Come on.

47:14.735 --> 47:15.936
(GRUNTS SOFTLY)

47:21.509 --> 47:22.943
(SLURPS)

47:27.848 --> 47:29.182
Okay, close your eyes.

47:30.784 --> 47:33.453
Are you ready
to love me even more?

47:35.255 --> 47:37.390
Look. Open your eyes.

47:38.291 --> 47:39.423
Is that peanut butter?

47:39.425 --> 47:40.861
Ha. (CHUCKLES)

47:41.261 --> 47:42.628
(SNIFFS)

47:42.630 --> 47:44.063
(SIGHS)

47:45.633 --> 47:46.967
RICHARD: Do you want a hand?

47:47.568 --> 47:48.802
No. I got it.

47:49.335 --> 47:50.771
(TAMI GRUNTS)

47:54.474 --> 47:56.173
(RICHARD GROANS)

47:56.175 --> 47:57.576
Oh.

47:57.578 --> 47:59.811
How much do you
love me right now?

47:59.813 --> 48:01.882
- (RICHARD MOANS)
- Huh?

48:03.751 --> 48:05.118
- Is it good?
- RICHARD: Mmm.

48:06.887 --> 48:09.023
(MUFFLED) It's so good.

48:12.425 --> 48:13.761
(MOANS)

48:16.797 --> 48:18.197
Oh, my God.

48:21.769 --> 48:23.102
RICHARD: Wow.

48:23.804 --> 48:25.637
So what do you think of that?

48:25.639 --> 48:28.072
- Huh?
- TAMI: It's so red.

48:28.074 --> 48:29.808
- RICHARD: Come on.
- What?

48:29.810 --> 48:31.009
What, is that
how you'd describe

48:31.011 --> 48:33.077
a painting by Monet? Red?

48:33.079 --> 48:34.746
- If it was red, I would.
- Red.

48:34.748 --> 48:36.648
- Yeah.
- (BOTH CHUCKLE)

48:36.650 --> 48:38.316
RICHARD: No. No.
That sunset's not red.

48:38.318 --> 48:43.156
That sunset
is beet-dyed pomegranate.

48:43.591 --> 48:46.026
(BOTH LAUGH)

48:47.193 --> 48:51.195
Ladies and gentlemen,
Bob Ross. (LAUGHS)

48:51.197 --> 48:52.931
Can you see... I say
it's kind of got a beety...

48:52.933 --> 48:54.032
It's definitely red.

48:54.034 --> 48:55.634
RICHARD: No, no, no.
With a hit

48:55.636 --> 48:57.769
of mandarin and flax

48:57.771 --> 49:00.672
and the faintest hint
of carnelian.

49:00.674 --> 49:02.708
Red. (CHUCKLES)

49:02.710 --> 49:04.442
Red sky at night.

49:04.444 --> 49:06.013
Sailor's delight.

49:07.881 --> 49:09.917
Who the hell is Bob Ross,
anyway?

49:10.618 --> 49:12.251
You don't know
who Bob Ross is?

49:13.319 --> 49:14.251
Should I?

49:14.253 --> 49:16.655
He's like
the master of kitsch.

49:16.657 --> 49:18.589
Uh, he's like
a modern-day Monet.

49:18.591 --> 49:21.592
You would love him. (CHUCKLES)

49:21.594 --> 49:24.029
- (CHUCKLES)
- Wait a second...

49:24.031 --> 49:25.496
- Aw.
- (RICHARD LAUGHING)

49:25.498 --> 49:29.668
- Wait, let me see you. Wait...
- (BOTH LAUGH)

49:29.670 --> 49:30.802
Your cheeks,
they're going to...

49:30.804 --> 49:31.970
RICHARD: Let me guess,
they're red?

49:31.972 --> 49:33.839
No, no.
It's definitely not red.

49:33.841 --> 49:38.209
More like, um,
a sizzling salmon ketchup.

49:38.211 --> 49:39.412
(BOTH LAUGH)

49:43.349 --> 49:45.052
(BOAT CREAKING)

49:49.288 --> 49:50.289
RICHARD: Tam?

49:51.357 --> 49:52.358
What is it?

49:54.795 --> 49:56.229
TAMI: Hold on.

50:02.602 --> 50:04.537
We're off sixty miles.

50:06.006 --> 50:08.274
And we lost a degree
of latitude.

50:08.641 --> 50:10.042
We... How?

50:10.044 --> 50:12.176
TAMI: I don't know!

50:12.178 --> 50:14.980
Maybe the clock's not working?

50:14.982 --> 50:18.182
(GRUNTS) Or I messed up
the math or something?

50:18.184 --> 50:21.153
We're over eighteen hundred
miles from Hawaii.

50:21.155 --> 50:23.354
Fricking rudder's not helping.

50:23.356 --> 50:27.861
(EXHALES) It's making it
impossible to stay on course.

50:32.365 --> 50:34.434
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

50:39.173 --> 50:40.906
Oi, no, no, no.
We need to ration now.

50:40.908 --> 50:42.373
Okay, you wanna
starve to death?

50:42.375 --> 50:43.875
You wanna be a victim,
be my guest.

50:43.877 --> 50:45.043
You make it sound like
it's a choice.

50:45.045 --> 50:46.978
- It is a choice, Tam.
- It's not a choice!

50:46.980 --> 50:49.449
- (METAL CREAKING)
- (TAMI SIGHS)

50:50.249 --> 50:52.485
- (CREAKING CONTINUES)
- Shut up!

50:53.120 --> 50:54.287
(GRUNTS)

50:56.422 --> 50:58.158
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

51:01.762 --> 51:04.098
(WINCING AND PANTING)

51:05.631 --> 51:06.632
You okay?

51:09.402 --> 51:11.268
(WINCING)

51:11.270 --> 51:12.206
(GROANS)

51:13.473 --> 51:15.142
(TAMI PANTS)

51:44.504 --> 51:46.506
(GRUNTING)

51:54.214 --> 51:56.647
TAMI: It has a jib
caught on it.

51:56.649 --> 51:57.783
I can't get it off.

51:57.785 --> 51:59.750
Maybe it'll have
to just trail.

51:59.752 --> 52:01.420
And create all that drag?

52:01.889 --> 52:03.456
(PANTING)

52:16.669 --> 52:17.670
(GRUNTING)

52:26.746 --> 52:28.414
(CONTINUES GRUNTING)

53:01.014 --> 53:02.448
(SNIFFS)

53:03.150 --> 53:04.684
(EXHALES DEEPLY)

53:09.857 --> 53:11.457
(RICHARD WINCING)

53:16.864 --> 53:18.664
- Babe?
- How is it?

53:19.465 --> 53:20.466
It's okay.

53:46.592 --> 53:48.594
(BREATHES HEAVILY)

53:53.166 --> 53:54.634
(RICHARD WINCING)

54:03.911 --> 54:05.745
(RICHARD BREATHING SHARPLY)

54:18.025 --> 54:19.659
(GRUNTING)

54:35.075 --> 54:37.175
RICHARD: Is everything okay
down there?

54:37.177 --> 54:38.312
Yeah.

54:43.283 --> 54:45.118
We're running low on water.

54:48.121 --> 54:49.855
Seven cans of sardines.

54:50.723 --> 54:51.891
(CLEARS THROAT)

54:54.827 --> 54:56.296
Nine cans...

54:57.830 --> 55:01.099
of God knows what.

55:01.101 --> 55:03.667
Let's pray for peaches.

55:03.669 --> 55:06.173
Fortunately, I think
it's gonna be beans.

55:08.308 --> 55:09.875
Three cans of Spam.

55:10.810 --> 55:12.179
Ugh.

55:18.251 --> 55:19.950
Thank God,
the bloody hot sauce

55:19.952 --> 55:21.152
didn't break though.

55:21.154 --> 55:22.755
This isn't gonna
last us a week.

55:23.823 --> 55:24.824
Well...

55:27.361 --> 55:29.296
We can supplement
with protein.

55:32.065 --> 55:33.398
TAMI: I'm not doing that.

55:33.400 --> 55:35.599
- I'm not gonna kill any fish.
- Why not?

55:35.601 --> 55:37.801
'Cause I'm not gonna
make something suffer.

55:37.803 --> 55:39.703
That food's not gonna
last us till Hawaii.

55:39.705 --> 55:40.940
I know it's not.

55:43.542 --> 55:44.510
Sorry.

55:47.080 --> 55:48.814
My ribs are broken,

55:49.782 --> 55:51.485
my leg is shattered.

55:53.719 --> 55:55.222
I'm dead weight.

55:58.091 --> 55:59.592
(SIGHS)

56:13.672 --> 56:14.807
(GRUNTS)

56:20.980 --> 56:22.581
(GASPING)

56:24.717 --> 56:26.418
RICHARD: Just relax.

56:26.420 --> 56:27.853
Easy for you to say.

56:28.821 --> 56:31.291
All right, well, remember
it could be worse.

56:32.059 --> 56:33.460
Could die of hunger.

56:34.094 --> 56:35.761
(GRUNTS FRUSTRATEDLY)

56:36.629 --> 56:37.663
(INHALES)

56:46.239 --> 56:47.640
(GRUNTS)

56:59.419 --> 57:01.952
(GRUNTS) I can't do it.

57:01.954 --> 57:02.922
It's too hard.

57:04.357 --> 57:05.858
(TAMI GRUNTING)

57:07.059 --> 57:08.395
RICHARD: It's okay.

57:13.266 --> 57:15.535
I can't do it. (GASPING)

57:19.106 --> 57:20.307
(SHUSHING)

57:42.962 --> 57:44.797
(LAUGHING)

57:52.606 --> 57:54.840
(THUNDER RUMBLING)

58:06.919 --> 58:08.321
(LAUGHS)

58:13.627 --> 58:15.694
TAMI: What you got
hiding in here?

58:27.507 --> 58:28.841
What?

58:31.977 --> 58:33.913
(CHUCKLES)

58:37.716 --> 58:40.353
No way. We've struck gold.

58:44.056 --> 58:45.958
Are you kidding me right now?

58:50.463 --> 58:52.399
We're gonna have a party!
(LAUGHS)

58:55.801 --> 58:57.870
A little touch of humanity...

59:20.660 --> 59:23.929
(SLOW GUITAR MUSIC PLAYING)

59:27.334 --> 59:30.437
(SINGING) <i>Well, I turn around
to look at you</i>

59:32.871 --> 59:35.342
<i>Light a cigarette</i>

59:37.009 --> 59:40.380
<i>I wish I had the guts
to bum one</i>

59:42.014 --> 59:45.882
<i>You don't know me yet</i>

59:45.884 --> 59:50.390
<i>And I hope that
I don't fall in love with you</i>

59:54.059 --> 59:58.298
<i>'Cause falling in love
just makes me blue</i>

59:59.532 --> 01:00:02.369
<i>Well, the music plays</i>

01:00:03.503 --> 01:00:10.377
<i>And you display your heart
for me to see</i>

01:00:11.411 --> 01:00:13.313
I wish you'd never met me...

01:00:17.651 --> 01:00:19.818
So you wouldn't be
in this mess.

01:00:24.189 --> 01:00:26.859
But I wouldn't have us
to remember.

01:00:30.829 --> 01:00:33.165
I wouldn't trade this
for anything.

01:00:36.603 --> 01:00:38.937
(SOFT GUITAR MUSIC PLAYING)

01:00:43.842 --> 01:00:47.844
(SINGING)
<i>'Cause falling in love</i>

01:00:47.846 --> 01:00:49.783
<i>Just makes me blue</i>

01:00:51.817 --> 01:00:56.019
<i>I had a beer and now I hear</i>

01:00:56.021 --> 01:01:01.060
<i>You calling out for me</i>

01:01:02.529 --> 01:01:07.367
<i>Well, I think that I just</i>

01:01:08.033 --> 01:01:14.374
<i>Fell in love with you</i>

01:01:16.576 --> 01:01:18.010
(LAUGHS)

01:01:18.478 --> 01:01:19.644
Come on.

01:01:19.646 --> 01:01:22.314
Hey, babe,
can I ask you something?

01:01:23.383 --> 01:01:24.417
Sure.

01:01:25.017 --> 01:01:26.386
How did your mum die?

01:01:29.589 --> 01:01:31.689
Uh, you really want to know?

01:01:31.691 --> 01:01:33.323
You don't have to tell me.

01:01:33.325 --> 01:01:34.960
Just... Curious.

01:01:36.161 --> 01:01:39.566
When I was seven,
she hung herself.

01:01:40.400 --> 01:01:41.401
What?

01:01:41.967 --> 01:01:43.668
Yeah, it... It's fine.

01:01:43.670 --> 01:01:44.970
It's...

01:01:46.439 --> 01:01:48.071
It's years ago now. So...

01:01:48.073 --> 01:01:49.376
Wow, I'm so sorry.

01:01:52.812 --> 01:01:54.445
But, Christ,
the first person in your life

01:01:54.447 --> 01:01:56.913
who dies is supposed
to be old, you know?

01:01:56.915 --> 01:01:58.418
Not your bloody mother.

01:02:02.087 --> 01:02:04.888
Uh, I think what I've done

01:02:04.890 --> 01:02:06.593
over the years
is just sort of...

01:02:07.827 --> 01:02:09.462
Sort of internalized.

01:02:10.430 --> 01:02:11.598
What? Internalized what?

01:02:12.799 --> 01:02:16.301
Her voice, I guess.

01:02:16.603 --> 01:02:17.769
Yeah.

01:02:17.771 --> 01:02:20.370
Like, in my mind, I still...

01:02:20.372 --> 01:02:22.475
I still ask her
to take a look at things.

01:02:24.376 --> 01:02:26.943
And still listen to her
tell me

01:02:26.945 --> 01:02:29.747
if something is right
or wrong, or...

01:02:29.749 --> 01:02:31.350
What is she saying now?
(LAUGHS)

01:02:33.686 --> 01:02:34.987
Uh...

01:02:35.921 --> 01:02:37.354
(CHUCKLES)

01:02:37.356 --> 01:02:39.891
"So it's true
what they say, innit?

01:02:39.893 --> 01:02:43.128
"All men really do
wanna marry their mums."

01:02:43.730 --> 01:02:45.330
(RICHARD LAUGHS)

01:02:48.233 --> 01:02:50.934
Oh, fuck, did I just ask you
to marry me

01:02:50.936 --> 01:02:52.906
in the voice
of my dead mother?

01:02:53.506 --> 01:02:55.207
Oh, God.

01:02:57.911 --> 01:02:59.644
(CHUCKLES)

01:02:59.646 --> 01:03:01.612
Okay, let me...

01:03:01.614 --> 01:03:03.081
Let me try that one more time.

01:03:13.258 --> 01:03:14.393
I love you.

01:03:15.495 --> 01:03:17.327
TAMI: Mmm-hmm...

01:03:17.329 --> 01:03:20.332
And I know that
I wanna be with you forever.

01:03:24.436 --> 01:03:26.171
So, uh...

01:03:28.675 --> 01:03:29.943
Oh, my God.

01:03:33.613 --> 01:03:35.380
Will you please marry me?

01:03:36.850 --> 01:03:39.182
You're not supposed
to say "please."

01:03:39.184 --> 01:03:41.253
You make it sound like
it's a favor. (LAUGHS)

01:03:42.054 --> 01:03:43.788
Right. Uh... Okay.

01:03:43.790 --> 01:03:45.890
But yes, yes.

01:03:45.892 --> 01:03:47.660
- Should I...
- Of course.

01:03:51.296 --> 01:03:53.363
Sorry. I must have made it
too small.

01:03:53.365 --> 01:03:55.167
- Is that... Is that all right?
- Did you make this?

01:03:55.568 --> 01:03:56.634
Yes, well...

01:03:56.636 --> 01:03:59.269
But I promise when we get back
to the States,

01:03:59.271 --> 01:04:01.240
we can get you a real one.

01:04:01.508 --> 01:04:02.575
No.

01:04:05.645 --> 01:04:06.746
It's perfect.

01:04:21.694 --> 01:04:24.029
(RUMBLING)

01:04:33.205 --> 01:04:35.073
Oh, my God. Oh, my God.

01:04:36.308 --> 01:04:37.442
Hey!

01:04:39.646 --> 01:04:40.647
Hello!

01:04:45.284 --> 01:04:46.285
Hey!

01:04:49.454 --> 01:04:50.557
I'm right here!

01:04:52.090 --> 01:04:55.028
Stop! Hello!

01:04:55.628 --> 01:04:57.129
No. No...

01:04:57.564 --> 01:04:59.164
No! No!

01:05:05.437 --> 01:05:07.272
(WHIMPERING)

01:05:09.107 --> 01:05:10.710
No, no, no...

01:05:12.277 --> 01:05:16.047
How could you not see us?
We're right here!

01:05:16.049 --> 01:05:17.684
We're right here!

01:05:20.185 --> 01:05:21.752
Where did you go?

01:05:21.754 --> 01:05:23.255
(PANTING)

01:05:24.222 --> 01:05:25.692
Where did you go?

01:05:28.761 --> 01:05:30.329
I'm hallucinating?

01:05:31.196 --> 01:05:34.097
Am I hallucinating? (SOBS)

01:05:34.099 --> 01:05:36.734
Oh, my God,
we're gonna die out here!

01:05:36.736 --> 01:05:38.705
We're gonna die out here!

01:05:41.506 --> 01:05:42.675
RICHARD: We might.

01:05:43.910 --> 01:05:46.311
You're not supposed
to say that!

01:05:47.145 --> 01:05:48.411
You'd rather I lied to you?

01:05:48.413 --> 01:05:50.413
Yes, please lie to me.

01:05:50.415 --> 01:05:53.350
Just tell me
it's gonna be okay.

01:05:53.352 --> 01:05:55.220
Tell me that this is real.

01:05:56.221 --> 01:05:57.824
RICHARD:
What does that even mean?

01:05:58.825 --> 01:06:00.325
(RICHARD GROANS)

01:06:04.931 --> 01:06:06.864
(TAMI GROANS)

01:06:06.866 --> 01:06:08.735
We're probably dead already.

01:06:10.535 --> 01:06:13.505
RICHARD: Exhausted...
Dehydrated...

01:06:14.841 --> 01:06:16.541
Delirious, uh...

01:06:19.211 --> 01:06:22.212
Yeah. But you're not dead.

01:06:22.214 --> 01:06:23.650
(SOBS QUIETLY)

01:06:46.773 --> 01:06:48.775
(SNIFFS, GROANS SOFTLY)

01:07:02.922 --> 01:07:05.321
Okay. Wake up.

01:07:05.323 --> 01:07:08.326
Baby, you've got to drink
some water. Open.

01:07:12.999 --> 01:07:15.833
- More. One more.
- Uh-uh.

01:07:15.835 --> 01:07:16.836
Come on.

01:07:18.336 --> 01:07:20.303
You have to eat something too.

01:07:20.305 --> 01:07:22.472
It's more important
you have it.

01:07:22.474 --> 01:07:25.277
TAMI: There's plenty for me.

01:07:25.845 --> 01:07:27.212
Open.

01:07:28.081 --> 01:07:29.614
Dammit, take a bite.

01:07:30.415 --> 01:07:32.250
You have to eat something.

01:07:39.624 --> 01:07:42.492
You let me sleep
through the night again?

01:07:42.494 --> 01:07:43.462
Yeah.

01:07:44.229 --> 01:07:45.898
And another night.

01:07:47.800 --> 01:07:49.601
And another day.

01:07:52.071 --> 01:07:54.774
Just wake me up
when we get to Hawaii.

01:07:55.775 --> 01:07:56.941
Guess what?

01:07:56.943 --> 01:08:00.477
We only have 690 miles to go.

01:08:00.479 --> 01:08:02.581
- (TAMI CHUCKLES)
- Only?

01:08:03.149 --> 01:08:04.817
Yeah, only, baby.

01:08:07.053 --> 01:08:09.488
No, no. Stay awake.
Look at me.

01:08:11.057 --> 01:08:13.558
Look... Look, look, look...

01:08:15.862 --> 01:08:17.595
I'm the...

01:08:19.397 --> 01:08:21.633
I'm the one
who crosses the horizon.

01:08:25.203 --> 01:08:26.939
I'm a real sailor!

01:08:32.912 --> 01:08:34.881
(WIND WHISTLING)

01:08:42.854 --> 01:08:43.856
Whoa!

01:08:44.991 --> 01:08:46.622
What was that?

01:08:46.625 --> 01:08:48.928
Babe, you've got to come
see this!

01:08:55.367 --> 01:08:57.033
Is that a land bird?

01:08:57.036 --> 01:08:58.868
Yeah.

01:08:58.871 --> 01:09:01.437
What's it doing
this far from shore?

01:09:01.439 --> 01:09:03.540
I don't know. The wind
must have blown her in.

01:09:03.542 --> 01:09:04.977
All the way from land?

01:09:05.912 --> 01:09:07.279
I think so.

01:09:09.548 --> 01:09:11.050
It's remarkable, right?

01:09:19.357 --> 01:09:21.294
Should we be worried?

01:09:24.296 --> 01:09:26.032
Hey, take the wheel,
I've just got to check this.

01:09:30.203 --> 01:09:31.600
(RADIO BEEPS)

01:09:31.603 --> 01:09:32.837
MAN: (ON RADIO) <i>A warning
to those in the Pacific.</i>

01:09:32.839 --> 01:09:34.470
<i>High winds
and expected rainfall</i>

01:09:34.471 --> 01:09:36.538
<i>are now changed to
a tropical depression</i>

01:09:36.541 --> 01:09:37.942
<i>forming off Central America,</i>

01:09:37.944 --> 01:09:40.010
<i>and is now
classified as a Class 4.</i>

01:09:40.011 --> 01:09:42.645
<i>It's moving quickly
and increasing in strength,</i>

01:09:42.647 --> 01:09:45.715
<i>currently at 12 degrees north
and 107 degrees</i>

01:09:45.716 --> 01:09:47.184
<i>and moving west at 12 knots.</i>

01:09:47.185 --> 01:09:48.953
Babe, that's not good...

01:09:48.955 --> 01:09:51.720
<i>And a repeat, for those of you
just tuning in.</i>

01:09:51.723 --> 01:09:53.926
- Babe?
- Just one sec, please.

01:09:56.329 --> 01:10:00.463
Right, so we're at 11 north
and 123 west.

01:10:00.465 --> 01:10:02.233
That's well over
1,000 miles away

01:10:02.235 --> 01:10:03.833
from the center of the storm.

01:10:03.835 --> 01:10:06.605
It should die out
before it reaches us, but...

01:10:07.940 --> 01:10:09.173
We have to watch this one.

01:10:09.175 --> 01:10:11.041
What if we just alter
our course?

01:10:11.043 --> 01:10:11.944
RICHARD: Huh?

01:10:12.979 --> 01:10:14.311
We cut north,
give the storm a wider berth.

01:10:14.313 --> 01:10:15.847
What do you think of that?

01:10:22.721 --> 01:10:24.556
RICHARD:
You're right, let's do it.

01:10:26.025 --> 01:10:28.725
We need to make sure
everything is secure.

01:10:28.727 --> 01:10:30.361
Yeah, we need to tack first.

01:10:30.363 --> 01:10:32.098
All right, let's tack.

01:10:43.276 --> 01:10:45.175
(THUNDER RUMBLING)

01:10:45.177 --> 01:10:47.477
- All right, lock it up.
- Yep.

01:10:47.479 --> 01:10:48.711
We don't want
any stuff flying around

01:10:48.713 --> 01:10:50.515
in case the storm hits.

